<p><b>Richard Allen Posner</b> (born <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1939-01-11"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="01-11"><a href="/wiki/January_11" title="January 11">January 11</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/1939" title="1939">1939</a></span>, in <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>) is currently a judge on the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Court_of_Appeals_for_the_Seventh_Circuit" title="United States Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit">United States Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit</a> in <a href="/wiki/Chicago" title="Chicago">Chicago</a>. He helped start the <a href="/wiki/Law_and_economics" title="Law and economics">law and economics</a> movement while a professor at the <a href="/wiki/University_of_Chicago_Law_School" title="University of Chicago Law School">University of Chicago Law School</a>; he currently serves as a senior lecturer at the Law School.</p>
<p>Posner is the author of nearly 40 books on jurisprudence, legal philosophy, and several other topics, including <i>The Problems of Jurisprudence;</i> <i>Sex and Reason;</i> <i><a href="/wiki/Overcoming_Law" title="Overcoming Law">Overcoming Law</a>;</i> <i>Law, Pragmatism and Democracy;</i> and <i>The Problematics of Moral and Legal Theory.</i> One journal has identified Posner as the most cited legal scholar of all time.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> He is considered to be one of the most respected judges in the United States.<sup id="cite_ref-nytimes_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nytimes-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
